        <h2 class="article__subheader">Prototype & Test</h2>

        <p>This took us right into the last two phases of the Design Thinking process: Prototyping and Testing. Our first prototype had a few key objectives:</p>

        <div class="heading-lockup">
          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Objective 1</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Provide more context about what‚Äôs currently happening in the system</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Objective 2</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Enable Green Line officials to keep each other updated about non-emergency issues</h4>
          </div>

          <div class="heading-lockup__item">
            <h5 class="heading-lockup__subheading">Objective 3</h5>
            <h4 class="heading-lockup__heading">Improve the fidelity of our data by making crucial train sheet data digital</h4>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>These objectives took the shape of an experience that showed train location, operator information, reported issues, and train sheets. We created this experience as a low-fidelity clickable prototype to start, so we could get it in the hands of officials quickly to hear their feedback and iterate on the design. This prototype wasn‚Äôt functional‚Äìit was a series of static screens created in a design program called Sketch, and linked together in a prototyping tool called InVision.</p>

        <p>We went back out to our interviewees and showed them the prototype on our phones to get their feedback. We asked questions like ‚ÄúWhat‚Äôs happening on this screen? What information is missing here? When would you use this feature? What would you do next?‚Äù After multiple rounds of showing and iterating on our prototype, we started to have a clearer idea of what we wanted to build for our first version of the product, our MVP.</p>

